and":"Georgeham, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1535–27 Jan 1599":"1535–27 januari 1599","1535–1599":"1535–1599","1560–1608":"1560–1608","1505–1585":"1505–1585","1503–1581":"1503–1581","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1599":"1599","1585":"1585","1560":"1560","1581":"1581","about 1585":"circa 1585","27 Jan 1599":"27 januari 1599","1608":"1608","1505":"1505","Braunton, Devon, England":"Braunton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Georgeham, Devonshire, England":"Georgeham, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1535–27 Jan 1599":"1535–27 January 1599","1535–1599":"1535–1599","1560–1608":"1560–1608","1505–1585":"1505–1585","1503–1581":"1503–1581","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1599":"1599","1585":"1585","1560":"1560","1581":"1581","about 1585":"about 1585","27 Jan 1599":"27 January 1599","1608":"1608","1505":"1505","Braunton, Devon, England":"Braunton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Georgeham, Devonshire, England":"Georgeham, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Perrin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English: from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Perrin</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perine  ,   Perrine  , and   Prine  .","History: Henri Perrin from Louargat in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany (France), married Jeanne Merrin in Montreal, QC, in 1661. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variants or altered forms <i>Perrine</i> and <i>Pareyn</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. One of the Huguenot ancestors was Daniel Perrin (1642–1719), nicknamed <i>The Huguenot</i>, who arrived in New York in 1665, aboard the <i>Philip</i>, and settled first in NJ and later on Staten Island. Among his descendants the surname is common in the altered forms <i>Perrine</i>, <i>Perine</i> and <i>Prine</i>. The Staten Island community of Huguenot is named after Daniel Perrin and other Huguenots who settled in the area during the late 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Prine","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Perrin  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of Dutch   Pruyn   or perhaps of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","History: The surname <i>Prine</i> is established among the descendants of the Huguenot immigrant Daniel Perrin (1642–1719); see   Perrin  ."]},{"name":"Pierre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Antoine, Yves, Michel, Jean Claude, Mireille, Jean Robert, Francois, Monique, Raoul, Serge.","French, Walloon, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian:","from the personal name <i>Pierre</i>, French form of   Peter   (see also below). This is one of the most frequent surnames in Haiti (along with   Jean   and   Joseph  ) and in Saint Martin. It is also established elsewhere in the West Indies (e.g. in Trinidad and Tobago, Saint Lucia, Grenada, and Bahamas)."]},{"name":"Perren","meanings":["French and English (of French Huguenot origin): variant of   Perrin  ."]},{"name":"Parren","meanings":["English: variant of   Perrin  ."]},{"name":"Perrine","meanings":["French: from the feminine form of   Perrin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","English: variant of   Perrin  . This surname is now rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: The surname <i>Perrine</i> of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with its original form   Perrin   in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Parran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique.","Altered form of French   Perrin  . This surname was brought to England by the Huguenots, but has died out there.","In some cases possibly also southern French: topographic name from Occitan <i>parran</i> ‘small garden behind a house’. This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Perrins","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Perrin  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Perrin was born in 1535, in Braunton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Perrin, was 30 and his mother, Mary Selwoode Perrin, was 32. He had at least 1 daughter. He died on 27 January 1599, in Georgeham, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1535–27 Jan 1599":"1535–27. jaanuar 1599","1535–1599":"1535–1599","1560–1608":"1560–1608","1505–1585":"1505–1585","1503–1581":"1503–1581","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1599":"1599","1585":"1585","1560":"1560","1581":"1581","about 1585":"umbes 1585","27 Jan 1599":"27. jaanuar 1599","1608":"1608","1505":"1505","Braunton, Devon, England":"Braunton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Georgeham, Devonshire, England":"Georgeham, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1535–27 Jan 1599":"1535–27. tammikuuta 1599","1535–1599":"1535–1599","1560–1